@PREV "RequirementsENG"
@TOC "GettingStartedENG"
@REM KEY 0 0 "GettingStartedENG" "Installation"
@{U}Installation@{UU}

   Laplace offers an installation script. Usually there should be no  problem,
just enter the  destination directory and  everything will be  copied to  this
place. Usually it is not necessary to use @{I}Expert @{UI} mode, because all files  are
copied to this directory and there is no danger of overwriting any files  that
are not  related to  Laplace. The  script  will also  create backups  of  your
Projects and Include files, so there is no danger of loosing these.

   The assign @{B}Laplace:@{UB} is  obsolete, please remove it,  if it is somewhere  in
your user-startup. Laplace might get confused by it!

@ENDNODE
@NODE "EnvironmentENG"
@TITLE "Environment variables"
@NEXT "CmdOptionsENG"
@PREV "InstallationENG"
@TOC "GettingStartedENG"
@REM KEY 0 0 "GettingStartedENG" "Environment variables"
@{U}Environment variables@{UU}

   When Laplace is started, it first  checks some @{I}environment variables @{UI}.  You
can modify these variables with the DOS command @{B}SetEnv@{UB}, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} SetEnv LAPLACELANGUAGE english

   They are stored as small text files in the @{B}ENV:@{UB} directory. The contents  of
this directory are only valid  until you reset or  turn off your computer.  To
set a @{I}environment variable @{UI}  permanently, you have to  copy it to the  @{B}ENVARC:@{UB}
directory after you set it, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} copy ENV:LAPLACELANGUAGE ENVARC:

   Laplace recognizes the following @{I}environment variables @{UI}:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}LAPLACELANGUAGE@{UB} - Select the  language to use. If  this variable is  not
   set (or set to an empty string), the system's default language is used.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}LAPLACEHOME@{UB} - Set the home directory for Laplace. This is the  directory
   where Laplace has been installed to, e.g. @{B}Work:Laplace/@{UB}. This is set au-
   tomatically when Laplace is started from the WORKBENCH.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}LAPLACEQUIET@{UB} - If this  variable is set to  @{B}TRUE@{UB}, Laplace will not  open
   it's start window.  This window is  reported to cause  problems on  some
   systems that's why you can disable it.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}LAPLACEERRHANDLER@{UB} - If this variable  is set to @{B}FALSE@{UB}, the  installation
   of the @{I}ErrorHandler @{UI} is inhibited.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}LAPLACELOG@{UB} -  Select a  path for  a protocol  file, e.g.  @{B}T:Laplace.log@{UB}.
   Laplace prints all actions performed during startup into this file.  You
   usually don't need it, but if Laplace refuses to start for some  unknown
   reason, you can set this variable and then send the generated file to me
   - I might find what the problem was.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}LAPLACEPREFS@{UB}   -   Set   the   path   for   the   preferences   file.
   @{B}Data/Prefs/Laplace.prefs@{UB} is the  default. If you  specify another  file,
   the preferences are loaded from and saved to this file.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}TMP@{UB}, @{B}LAPLACETMP@{UB} - Set the directory for temporary files. The default  is
   @{B}T:@{UB}. @{B}TMP@{UB} is overridden by @{B}LAPLACETMP@{UB}.

@ENDNODE
@NODE "CmdOptionsENG"
@TITLE "Command line options"
@PREV "EnvironmentENG"
@TOC "GettingStartedENG"
@REM KEY 0 0 "GettingStartedENG" "Command line options"
@{U}Command line options@{UU}

   After reading the @{I}environment  variables @{UI}, Laplace  processes the @{I}options  @{UI}
specified in the command line invoking Laplace, e.g.
@{B}@{BG FILL}@{FG FILLTEXT}>@{UB}@{BG BACKGROUND}@{FG TEXT} bin/Laplace --language deutsch

   An @{I}option @{UI} overwrites a value set by an @{I}environment variable @{UI}.

   Laplace recognizes the following @{I}command line options @{UI}:

 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--help@{UB}, @{B}-h@{UB}, @{B}-?@{UB} - Displays a brief list of the available @{I}command line op-@{UI}
   @{I}tions @{UI} and exists immediately.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--language @{I}name @{UB}@{UI}, @{B}-l @{I}name @{UB}@{UI} - Select the language to use. If this  option
   is not given, the value of the @{I}environment variable @{UI} @{B}LAPLACELANGUAGE@{UB}  or
   the system's default language is used.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--home @{I}path @{UB}@{UI}, @{B}-H @{I}path @{UB}@{UI} - Set the home path for Laplace. This is the  di-
   rectory where Laplace has been installed to, e.g. @{B}Work:Laplace/@{UB}.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--quiet@{UB}, @{B}-q@{UB} - If this option is given, Laplace will not open it's  start
   window. This window is reported to cause problems on some systems that's
   why you can disable it.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--logfile @{I}path @{UB}@{UI} - Select a path for a protocol file, e.g. @{B}T:Laplace.log@{UB}.
   Laplace prints all actions performed during startup into this file.  You
   usually don't need it, but if Laplace refuses to start for some  unknown
   reason, you can set this variable and then send the generated file to me
   - I might find what the problem was.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--prefs @{I}path @{UB}@{UI}, @{B}-p @{I}path @{UB}@{UI} - Set the path for the preferences file. If this
   option is not given, the value of the @{I}environment variable @{UI} @{B}LAPLACEPREFS@{UB}
   or the default preferences path @{B}Data/Prefs/Laplace.prefs@{UB} is used. If you
   specify another file, the preferences are loaded from and saved to  this
   file.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--tmp @{I}path @{UB}@{UI}, @{B}-t @{I}path @{UB}@{UI} - Set the path for temporary files. If this option
   is not given, the value of the @{I}environment variable @{UI} @{B}LAPLACETMP@{UB} or@{B}TMP@{UB} or
   the default @{B}T:@{UB} is used.
 @{B}·@{UB} @{B}--no-errhandler@{UB} - Disables  the installation  of the  @{I}ErrorHandler @{UI}.  If
   this option  is  not given,  the  value  of the  @{I}environment  variable  @{UI}
   @{B}LAPLACEERRHANDLER@{UB} is used.

@ENDNODE
